Yeah. So code review sessions I think are like really crucial, especially if you are helping

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:42.879
teams transition from other tools into our other open source languages. I think the most important

00:51:42.879 --> 00:51:48.479
thing about a code review session is you have to upfront declare a norm on the fact that this is

00:51:48.479 --> 00:51:53.919
not going to be used for performance evaluations. I think one of the things that we have noticed

00:51:53.919 --> 00:52:00.159
culturally sometimes is that people will look at code review as a negative performance indicator.

00:52:00.159 --> 00:52:06.719
It is not. It is how we all get better and how we all improve our capability. So it also depends on

00:52:06.719 --> 00:52:10.239
once you've kind of established that norm, then you can set up your code review sessions.

00:52:10.959 --> 00:52:15.199
There's different ways that you can do it. You can do large drop in sessions where people bring

00:52:15.199 --> 00:52:19.439
problems and then you work through the problems all together or do a session where you're all

00:52:19.439 --> 00:52:24.320
reviewing each other's work in a larger group. You can do one-on-one if individuals prefer to

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:29.120
have that kind of one-on-one intimacy. It really depends on the user on the study team and like

00:52:29.120 --> 00:52:33.840
what it is that they are comfortable with. The big things that we're looking for in code review

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:40.000
sessions are, and this might sound dumb for people, but it is a problem that we face very frequently,

00:52:40.560 --> 00:52:44.399
is are people actually using packages? So one of the things I will often see

00:52:45.040 --> 00:52:50.879
is an individual will write a custom function to deal with like dates when they could just

00:52:50.879 --> 00:52:55.919
literally use like functions that are available within tidyverse. So we are always looking at

00:52:55.919 --> 00:53:01.360
things like how do we help improve like speed efficiency? How do we help individuals realize

00:53:01.360 --> 00:53:06.719
that, you know, this really hard thing that I'm trying to do with date time, there's a whole suite

00:53:06.719 --> 00:53:11.040
of functions within tidyverse that I can do, that I can use. And that's the type of thing that

00:53:11.040 --> 00:53:16.159
we typically look for. If the users are more advanced, maybe we're looking at like how do we

00:53:16.159 --> 00:53:21.360
deal with like code performance when it relates to Bayesian statistical analysis. That's a really

00:53:21.360 --> 00:53:26.879
hard thing that you have to do. You need a lot of like expertise. So code review, I guess long

00:53:26.879 --> 00:53:32.239
story short, code reviews are the full gamut. But at the end of the day, the very first thing you

00:53:32.239 --> 00:53:37.280
need to do is norm on the fact that this is not for performance review or have any impact on

00:53:37.280 --> 00:53:43.600
performance. It's just how do we improve our deliverables as a whole? I feel like the next

